### Interpretation

* **Onset collapsed** from 2.5–67.5 µm to 2.5–12.5 µm: the curved fit
  now hugs the tissue boundary on all six subjects including 790322 /
  788406, which were the stubborn cases in both v1 image-only and
  N13.  790322's x≈2000 µm dip is now captured by the quadratic.
* **above_frac is higher than N22** (5–10 % vs ≤ 0.08 %) because we
  have no ROI clamp.  N22's `_clamp_to_roi_envelope` lifts the surface
  until ≤ 10 % of per-tile cells sit above it — that depends on
  centroid data we deliberately aren't using here.  v3 itself reports
  `above_frac = 1.44 %` for 790322 without the clamp, and we're in
  the same regime but on the combined multi-channel volume (which has
  more above-surface noise than the per-channel signal N22 uses).
* **CZ residual MAD rose** (1.3 → 4.7 µm) simply because we now
  have ~2500 column tops per CZ stack instead of 25 tile centres —
  more samples means more spread.  The plane passes through a scalar
  fit, so MAD was artificially low.  4–7 µm RMS against the tissue
  boundary is biologically reasonable.
* **CZ tilts stayed low** (2.7–6.1°) — the curved fit hasn't over-fit
  the cz centroid surface; the p, q, r coefficients are small in CZ.

## Parameters

| knob | HCR | CZ | source |
|---|---|---|---|
| xy_tile_um (anchor) | 150 | 80 | HCR: one landmark; CZ: tighter for smaller volume |
| column_stride_um | 10 | 8 | N22 uses 10 for HCR; CZ is smaller in µm |
| band_um | 150 | 100 | N22 HCR = 150 |
| relative_margin | 0.25 | 0.25 | N22 default |
| min_signal_abs_frac | 0.20 | 0.20 | N22 default |
| min_thick_um | 10 | 10 | N22 default |
| target_quantile | 0.70 | 0.70 | N22 default |

All distribution-driven; no hand-tuned absolute intensities.

## What works, what doesn't

### Works
* HCR quadratic surface now follows curvature (visible in
  walkthrough figures — cyan plane anchor vs red quadratic surface).
* CZ surface stays excellent (residual MAD 4–7 µm, above% ≤ 7 %).
* All six subjects converge; no failed subject.
* Onset ≤ 12.5 µm across the board.

### Doesn't yet
* **Above_frac** without the ROI clamp sits at 5–10 %.  To close the
  gap with N22 we would need to either (a) apply the ROI clamp (but
  this session is explicitly image-only) or (b) bias the fit deeper
  still (e.g. `target_quantile = 0.80`).  Worth a quick sweep.
* **782149 CZ above_frac = 6.6 %** is the highest — the fitted
  surface there sits slightly shallow.  Manual inspection of the
  walkthrough may show why (possibly the CZ buffer signal is
  unusually strong on that subject).

